<DOC><DOCNO> AP890721-0064 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-21-89 1001EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia 2ndLd-Writethru a0486 07-21 0304</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Cambodia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0486,0310</SECOND><HEAD>Refugee Camp Shelled; One Dead, 10 Wounded</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with relief officials saying appearspro-Vietnamese forces shelled camp. Pickup 6th, `The camp...'</HEAD><DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Cambodian refugee camp run bycommunist Khmer Rouge guerrillas came under heavy shelling todaythat killed one refugee and wounded 10, Western relief officialssaid.   One official said 27 shells crashed into the Site 8 camp inThailand near the Cambodian border. The three hours of shellingfollowed overnight fighting in the area, said a Thai securityofficial.   The U.N. Border Relief Operation declared the camp off limits torelief personnel for safety reasons.   Site 8 houses 40,000 refugees and is the main civilian campoperated by the Khmer Rouge, the largest guerrilla group fightingVietnamese occupation forces and allied Cambodian government troops.   Western relief officials said it appeared that Vietnamese-backedgovernment forces staged the attack.   In the past, the Khmer Rouge has shelled its own camps inmacabre attempts to exercise strict control over the refugees or toreduce their population. Widespread human rights violations havebeen reported in the camps.   The camp of thatched houses is in Thailand's eastern province ofPrachinburi and about a mile from the Cambodian border.   Fighting between pro-Vietnamese forces and the Khmer Rouge hasincreased along the border in recent days, as often is the casebefore diplomatic events and peace talks.   The Khmer Rouge and the other guerrilla groups are to hold talkswith the Vietnamese-installed government in Paris next week, thenattend an international conference on Cambodia starting July 30.   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in 1978 and toppled the brutal KhmerRouge regime. The Khmer Rouge were in power from 1975-1978.Hundreds of thousands of Cambodia's 8 million people died fromKhmer Rouge executions, famine and civil unrest.</TEXT></DOC>